White Cities. A single life spread across three vibrant American cities: Chicago, New York, and Los Angeles.

I chose the title as a bold statement that puts race right at the forefront of the music, as White did with his art. I want people to consider the whiteness of all the cities as a reminder of the overarching oppression pervading each place where White lived — and that his expression, birthed as the blues, is a testifying of the black experience in a white world.

The title also refers to the artist himself. It is my intention to musically represent the evolution of Charles White’s heart and mind— not just the subjects and messages of his works, but an accompanying examination of the person who created the works. Essentially a dedication to the man, his work, and the source of inspiration behind his works. 

March 3: G Livelab - Tampere, Finland
March 4: Savoy Theater - Helsinki, Finland
March 6: Wien Konzerthaus - Vienna, Austria
March 8: LantarenVenster - Rotterdam, Netherlands
March 9: Bozar - Brussels, Belgium
March 10: De Singel - Antwerp, Belgium
March 11: Festival Jazz Terrassa - Barcelona, Spain
March 12: Jazzclub Unterfahrt - Munich, Germany

“Love Letter III”
Just one of many brilliant pieces by artist and activist Charles White. I’m excited to hit the road and pay tribute to his life and work. Check my previous post for tour dates and go to geraldclayton.com/tour for ticket info.

🙏🏽✨

Oh and LA friends, sorry to miss the next few Tuesday Happenings at @samfirstbar. As usual, I’m being covered by some of the music’s finest- go check out the great @davidbinney tonight at 7:30pm

View of the spaceship 🚀 
Big thanks to the folks at @yasinewyork for graciously hooking up this super cool Reface CS synthesizer. It’s been perfect for this bass-less configuration. 

A few more concerts to go, a-journeying with these incredible magicians, paying tribute to maestro Charles White. 🙏🏽✨

#YamahaReFace #YamahaArtist

Whew, that’s a wrap! 
Huuuge love and thanks to my brothers in the music for their voices and visions on and off the bandstand. Traveling these European trails the past two weeks has been a joy. The songs, the sights, the communion, the discourse—all inspiring. I’m honored to call these incredible humans family and to serve the music and the mission together.
Thanks also to the hard working folks behind the scenes who organize year round to make these tours happen. To all the wonderful audiences who give us so much love and support. And lastly to maestro Charles White for having lived such an inspiring life, offering the world such a vast body of work and service. 

I’m on a train to Hamburg now, heart and mind full, excited to reconnect with more family members - @joesandersbass & @hutchmaniac - we’ll be at @laeiszhalle tomorrow night. 

Peace 
Love
🙏🏽✨

Happy Birthday Maestro @charleslloydsax.

European friends! I’m thrilled to be heading your way next month to make music with two legendary humans whom I love and admire dearly and greatly- @joesandersbass & @jeffballardmusic 

Hope to see you there! 

✌🏽 & ❤️

A week later and the music is still ringing in my ears. Thank you to everyone who made this year’s Monterey Jazz Festival so special. 

The Next Generation Jazz Orchestra— you all performed beautifully! It was a thrill to stand in front of you and watch you shine. 

The trio with @johnclaytonjazz & @jeffhamiltondrums. Too much love for words. A memory I’ll cherish forever. 

Flying with maestro @charleslloydsax, Reuben Rogers and @kadscott — an absolute joy and honor. Surreal to perform Forest Flower on that legendary stage. 

So much communion, love, and laughter. Old friends and heroes. Expressing immense gratitude and love to artistic director Tim Jackson for his decades of incredible service. Excited to welcome the new leadership and vision of the brilliant @darinatwater. 

I’m truly grateful to be a part of this magical ecosystem that is the @montereyjazzfestival 

🙏🏽❤️

Gerald Clayton, Elena Pinderhughes
2220 Arts + Archives
Sun, Jan 7 at 8:00 PM PST

About
Gerald Clayton joins us on Sunday night in the 2220 theater to play a solo piano set, and will then be accompanied by flutist Elena Pinderhughes for a second set afterwards. Mythscience presents!
~
“One could argue the entire history of the piano is encapsulated in [Gerald’s] playing, melting into a new creation altogether.” Gary Fukushima, Downbeat Magazine
January's appearance will be featuring Elena Pinderhughes, who at twenty-seven years old has established herself as one of the preeminent flautists in modern music. Her sound, steeped in tradition yet percolating with harmonic and rhythmic invention, has led her to sharing the stage with the likes of Herbie Hancock, Esperanza Spalding, and Carlos Santana.

📷 @ogata_photo
